description:
Will AI and AI agents replace God, steal your job, and change your future? Amjad Masad, Bret Weinstein, and Daniel Priestley debate the terrifying warning signs, and why you need to understand them now. 

In this debate, they explain: 
▫️Why AI threatens 50% of the global workforce.
▫️How AI agents are already replacing millions of jobs and how to use them to your advantage.
▫️How AI will disrupt creative industries and hijack human consciousness.
▫️The critical skills that will matter most in the AI-powered future.
▫️What parents must teach their kids now to survive the AI age.
▫️How to harness AI’s power ethically.

comments.text: Why does a teacher at the blackboard still have to ramble on about something that any average chatbot can now generate in a second? It all comes down to information, technology, and funding. In the past, information was mainly available to teachers; today, every pupil or student can access the same scope and quality of knowledge on their mobile phone or tablet. With the help of hyperlinks in Wikipedia or Kiwix, any topic can be studied—including context and connections. Interpretation and correct explanation of content is also possible when its exact meaning isn't immediately clear. One can ask a good chatbot, study referenced online sources, or enter an advanced query into a search engine. There are many options. In this way, almost any subject area can be mastered, especially in the descriptive sciences. Digital content has many advantages. Through hyperlinks, one can explore content contextually, find necessary connections, and clarify content ambiguities. This is often a major issue in traditional lecturing, which is why students learn so little. We must recognize that today, a chatbot can generate a high-quality explanation on the vast majority of topics in the descriptive sciences. For a general overview, this is more than sufficient. Just enter, for example, “German Confederation,” “Bourbon Restoration,” or “Weimar Republic,” etc. The same applies to geography, biology, and so on. For basic technical sciences, you can use tools like Mathway, PhyWiz, and Chemistry Cool. They solve technical problems and explain them in detail. Today’s education system must be of the highest quality and efficiency; otherwise, we have no chance of keeping up in a rapidly developing world. Schools will then only be necessary for applied sciences and hands-on training. Otherwise, it's just a waste of time, energy, money, manpower, and children's potential. Our educational system is outdated, inefficient, dysfunctional, and not very productive. It's only kept alive by the power of the education minister, not by the market forces of supply and demand, as is standard in a proper market environment. Without a deep audit, major reform, and fundamental rationalization of school processes, our business managers will continue to complain that school graduates and job applicants know almost nothing and have to be trained practically from scratch—as if they had never even gone to school. It’s a major disgrace to our education system. Period.
comments.author: @Truthseeker-cx46g

comments.text: Only very few people today fully realize how revolutionary the year 2025 is for human labor. It can perhaps only be compared to the Industrial Revolution or the discovery of how humans could make and maintain fire. The second half of the year will be absolutely groundbreaking in terms of human mental work. By the end of 2025, AI will be capable of essentially fully replacing human mental work, and two-thirds of employees will become obsolete and redundant. New models such as ChatGPT 5 and the full integration of AI models into the computer and application environment will contribute to this. Some applications, such as Ace AI Agent or Fellou AI Agent, are now very close to completion in beta testing. The vast majority of clerical and office agendas will then be automated into templates and available to the general public. Once humans are freed from mental and intellectual work, the technological world will focus on replacing manual labor with AI humanoid robots. This will likely happen in 2026 and finalize in 2027. Everything is almost ready; very advanced robotic hands are already being mass-produced in Tesla factories, and up to 20,000 new Optimus Gen 3 robots are to be completed by the end of 2025. These will then, in 2026, produce their more advanced Gen 4 and Gen 5 replicas in these factories at a volume of up to 200,000 per year. Other companies, especially in China, will add at least another million robots. The largest and most important global factories only need about one to two million robots for operation. Another minimum of five to ten million robots will be needed in agriculture, construction, and services. Capitalists see the opportunity to maximize their profits through AI robotization, and as soon as it is even slightly possible, they will not hesitate for a minute. They are powerful predators who only pursue profit and the maximum capitalization of their investments. Nothing else really matters in capitalism. That is all.

comments.text:
Two notes (~10 minutes in):

- Thank you for the pop-ups defining familiar terms, as they’re being used in this conversation. We all have an idea of what “open source” is, for example. Knowing what it means in discussion between these professionals starts us all on the same page.

- Yes, definitely more convos. I think you’d benefit from diversifying not merely field and position, but standpoint. Your panel is composed of an AI optimist (software engineer), an AI skeptic (evolutionary biologist), and an AI (without judgment) opportunist, I.e. someone who’s actively exploring its possibilities. But all four of you are entrepreneurs, of business and of self (again, no judgment), and the thrust of the conversation is “What can AI do to create new business opportunities and generate wealth?” 

Ten minutes in, and you’ve already synchronized, talking about God and elite marathoners and the implicit assumption that the “fittest” people (::nod to the evolutionary biologist::) will WANT to take the fullest advantage of AI’s opportunities. Not all of us will. To build out this discussion, you need to include the people who are perfectly capable of understanding (in this case) AI’s business potential, but do not share that mindset.
